SIMPLE: favorable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Favorable
<hw>Fa"vor*a*ble</hw> <pr>(f⟦amac⟧"v⟦etil⟧r*⟦adot⟧*b'l)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>favourable</asp>.]</altsp>
<ety>[F. <ets>favorable</ets>, L. <ets>favorabilis</ets> favored,
popular, pleasing, fr. <ets>favor</ets>. See <er>Favor</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of favor; favoring;
manifesting partiality; kind; propitious; friendly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lend <qex>favorable</qex> ears to our request.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord, thou hast been <qex>favorable</qex> unto thy land.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lxxxv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Conducive; contributing; tending to promote or
facilitate; advantageous; convenient.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A place very <qex>favorable</qex> for the making levies of
men.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The temper of the climate, <qex>favorable</qex> to generation,
health, and long life.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Beautiful; well-favored.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Fa"vora*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> --
<wf>Fa"vor*a*bly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>favorableness</qex> of the present times to all exertions
in the cause of liberty.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Favored</ent>⟦br⟧
